To avoid unpredictable behaviour and even a potential ConcurrentModificationException, instead of using enhanced for loop, use [Iterator][1], which supports removing element while iterating over them.

Alternatively, you could use simple for loop and iterate backwards:

    List&lt;String&gt; list;
    
    for(int i = list.size() - 1; i &gt;= 0; --i) {
            if(list.get(i).contains(&quot;bad&quot;)){
                    list.remove(i);
            }
    }


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Iterator.html

It&#39;s hard to follow your exact logic (since you didn&#39;t give us a full method, for example it&#39;s unclear where `injury` is coming from), but it seems you don&#39;t need to loop at all. Simply using `.contains()`, `.add()` and `.remove()` should suffice:

```
private addInjury(String section, String injury) {
  String storeKey = uuid + &quot;.&quot; + section;
  List&lt;String&gt; sevs = iStore.getStringList(storeKey);
  if (injury.equals(&quot;Broken&quot;)) {
    sevs.remove(&quot;Fracture&quot;); // no need to check if it&#39;s in sev, if it isn&#39;t this will do nothing.
  } else {
    sevs.remove(&quot;Intact&quot;); // depending on the desired logic, this could just go after the if outside of the else block.
  }
  if (!sevs.contains(injury)) {
    sevs.add(injury);
  }
  iStore.set(storeKey, sevs);
  store.saveStore();
}
```

