### Short Answer
Your validator should, as your model and your error message imply:
```lang-java
... implements ConstraintValidator&lt;LastName, String&gt;
```
And not `&lt;LastName, User&gt;`.

Accordingly, you should re-implement the `isValid(...)` method: accepting the last name `String` (and not the containing `User`).

If you want to use this annotation on `User` and `String` &quot;fields&quot;, you *must* implement an additional `ConstraintValidator&lt;LastName, ...&gt;`, with according &quot;API facade&quot;.

This *can* be wired/refered like:
```lang-java
@Constraint(
  validatedBy = {
    StringLastNameValidator.class, 
    UserLastNameValidator.class /*,...*/ 
  }
) // accepts array!;)
```
### Extended answer
Your (current) validator seems wrong (&quot;Mr. Jack Jack&quot; is invalid, while &quot;Mr `&lt;null&gt;` X&quot; valid!?), but should (if reasoned) be used **on `User`** &quot;fields&quot;, e.g (&quot;method parameter&quot; in this case) :
```lang-java
@PostMapping(&quot;/submitForm&quot;)
    public String handleSubmit(
  @Valid @LastName User user // ! ...
```
...to use it **inside `User`** (on `String` fields), stick to &quot;short answer&quot;.

